recordist: A couple of crows calling from about 10m up in neighboring Cottonwood trees.
remarks:
A couple of crows calling from about 10m up in neighboring Cottonwood trees.
The most interesting part of the cut may also be the most difficult to hear. Toward the end of the cut, one of the crows appears to be taking gulps of air and then hunching its back with its bill tucked down into its chest while making soft hoo-woo sounds @ approx 600Hz. There are 3 of these sounds: at 1:52, 1:57, and 2:03.
Also includes a rattle call toward the end.

recordist: They sing this song in a display flight, first going up and then falling in "parachutting". They were in the alpine tundra, we found many nests.
remarks:
They sing this song in a display flight, first going up and then falling in "parachutting". They were in the alpine tundra, we found many nests.
They have another alarm call, they may fly in circles above and around you calling for a short time before they leave. I guess they do that when you are close to the nest... but not always. The call was a short high note but I am not sure if I recorded it, I don't find it ( I am afraid I mixed it with the call of Luscinia svecica).

Recorded from about 10m using Olympus LS-10S and homemade parabolic reflector. Filtered low frequecies (below 2kHz) slightly for significant traffic / airplane noise.

recordist: Songs and calls from a wintering flock of 20-30 in a patch of scrub in oak savanna. This recording is comprised of several segments with slight breaks between them. Most of the time, the birds were calling, singing, and chasing eachother around the bushes. Occasionally small groups would make forays out into the grasses to forage, and then return.
remarks:
Songs and calls from a wintering flock of 20-30 in a patch of scrub in oak savanna. This recording is comprised of several segments with slight breaks between them. Most of the time, the birds were calling, singing, and chasing eachother around the bushes. Occasionally small groups would make forays out into the grasses to forage, and then return.
At approximately 8:36, a Northern Shrike appears. There's an alarm call from one of the sparrows and they all stop singing and dive into the thickest

recordist: In this track, most of the birds from the flock in XC127999 are out foraging in the grasses. Only a few birds are left behind and singing in the bushes, so it's possible to focus on just a single song at a time. Windy, cold, and overcast.
remarks:
In this track, most of the birds from the flock in XC127999 are out foraging in the grasses. Only a few birds are left behind and singing in the bushes, so it's possible to focus on just a single song at a time. Windy, cold, and overcast.
Filtered low frequencies slightly for wind, traffic, and airplane noise. Recorded with Olympus LS-10S and homemade parabolic reflector.

remarks:

The recording was made from a stationary location about 20 to 30 feet from the birds on average.
A set of 13 photographs with synchronization timing with this recording and showing from 1 to all 3 of the birds can be found at the following URL: http://www.flickr.com/photos/94309556@N05/sets/7215

recordist: Recording was done with internal mics on Olympus LS10 and amplified for clarity, otherwise no alterations. The bird was small by island standards, but fully feathered and capable of flight, so I cannot attempt to guess at age. It sat (nervously) about 10 meters from a trail in a deciduous tree in a 50 acre wooded habotat where the species is known to breed. It moved once to another tree, continued the 'searching' movements of its body. There was no set interval between vocalizations.
remarks: Recording was done with internal mics on Olympus LS10 and amplified for clarity, otherwise no alterations. Sage sparrow seen and heard singing on the north side of Apollo Park on a very windy day. This bird was recorded only about 30 km north of the southern edge of the range of this subspecies (sage sparrows that breed farther south in this area are from the belli subspecies).
Photographed.
The bird was in native, western Mojave Desert vegetation about 1.5 meters above the ground only a few tens of meters from non-native Aleppo Pines in Apollo Park. It was singing from the top of a bush.
